{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T22-21-58-423Z","slug":"beware-the-single-purpose-people","locale":"it","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T22:22:23.274Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-04-03--beware-the-single-purpose-people/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-04-03--beware-the-single-purpose-people/it/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/beware-the-single-purpose-people/it/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T22-21-58-423Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"589549661808bbda140a93d1cc1d1b94e45f65803955211732aca6ca7dd257ab","outputHash":"4844051d7e0ea9d81b171e3ea111c349344cbbfe91c03ec0ba3e84204cbf36d4","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that while the **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)** promotes modularity and clarity, its rigid application—prioritizing \"small\" over \"cohesive\"—leads to **over-fragmented codebases** and reduced developer productivity. It critiques developers (dubbed \"Single-Purpose People\") who enforce arbitrary boundaries (e.g., 5-line functions), resulting in **file system shrapnel**, **dependency tangles**, and **testing fragility**, particularly in frameworks like React/Redux. The author advocates for **pragmatic SRP**: grouping logically related code that changes together, emphasizing **conceptual cohesion** over atomicity. The tone is analytical and cautionary, using metaphors like \"Unix philosophy\" and \"Rube Goldberg Pattern\" to contrast idealism with practicality. Intended for developers and architects grappling with modular design","totalInputTokens":6379,"totalOutputTokens":6121,"totalCacheReadTokens":2048,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":13815,"totalCostUsd":0.00197936,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"10p","totalChunks":5,"totalInputTokens":6379,"totalOutputTokens":6121,"totalCacheReadTokens":2